"Dawson A.","Control of the annual cycle in birds: Endocrine constraints and plasticity in response to ecological variability",2008,"Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences","363","1497",,"1621","1633",,,10.1098/rstb.2007.0004,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-41149180234&partnerID=40&md5=8798dec64bdd2046861d6eec6e019b04","Centre for Ecology and Hydrology, Abbots Ripton, Huntingdon, Cambridgeshire PE28 2LS, United Kingdom","Dawson, A., Centre for Ecology and Hydrology, Abbots Ripton, Huntingdon, Cambridgeshire PE28 2LS, United Kingdom","This paper reviews information from ecological and physiological studies to assess how extrinsic factors can modulate intrinsic physiological processes. The annual cycle of birds is made up of a sequence of life-history stages: breeding, moult and migration. Each stage has evolved to occur at the optimum time and to last for the whole duration of time available. Some species have predictable breeding seasons, others are more flexible and some breed opportunistically in response to unpredictable food availability. Photoperiod is the principal environmental cue used to time each stage, allowing birds to adapt their physiology in advance of predictable environmental changes. Physiological (neuroendocrine and endocrine) plasticity allows non-photoperiodic cues to modulate timing to enable individuals to cope with, and benefit from, short-term environmental variability. Although the timing and duration of the period of full gonadal maturation is principally controlled by photoperiod, non-photoperiodic cues, such as temperature, rainfall or food availability, could potentially modulate the exact time of breeding either by fine-tuning the time of egg-laying within the period of full gonadal maturity or, more fundamentally, by modulating gonadal maturation and/or regression. The timing of gonadal regression affects the time of the start of moult, which in turn may affect the duration of the moult. There are many areas of uncertainty. Future integrated studies are required to assess the scope for flexibility in life-history strategies as this will have a critical bearing on whether birds can adapt sufficiently rapidly to anthropogenic environmental changes, in particular climate change. © 2007 The Royal Society.","Annual cycle in birds; Breeding season; Moult; Photoperiodism; Rainfall; Temperature","rain; adaptation; annual cycle; bird; breeding season; ecophysiology; endocrine system; food availability; life history trait; migration; molt; phenotypic plasticity; photoperiod; rainfall; sexual maturity; temperature effect; animal; bird; endocrine system; environment; molting; periodicity; photoperiodicity; physiology; population migration; review; season; sexual behavior; temperature; Animal Migration; Animals; Birds; Endocrine System; Environment; Molting; Periodicity; Photoperiod; Rain; Seasons; Sexual Behavior, Animal; Temperature; Aves",,,,,,"Ashmole, N.P., The biology of the wideawake or sooty tern Sterna fuscata on Ascension Island (1963) Ibis, 103, pp. 297-364; Barta, Z., McNamara, J.M., Houston, A.I., Weber, T.P., Hedenström, A., Feró, O., Optimal moult strategies in migratory birds Phil. Trans. R. Soc. B, , In press, doi:10.1098/rstb.2007.2136; Battley, P.F., Consistent annual schedules in a migratory shorebird (2006) Biol. Lett, 2, pp. 517-520. , doi:10.1098/rsbl.2006.0535; Bauchinger, U., Klaassen, M., Longer days in spring than in autumn accelerate migration speed of passerine birds (2005) J. Avian Biol, 36, pp. 3-5. , doi:10.1111/j.0908-8857.2005.03444.x; Beebe, K., Bentley, G.E., Hau, M., A seasonally breeding tropical bird lacks absolute photorefractoriness in the wild, despite high photoperiodic sensitivity (2005) Funct. Ecol, 19, pp. 505-512. , doi:10.1111/j.1365-2435.2005.00994.x; Bentley, G.E., Spar, B.D., MacDougall-Shackleton, S.A., Hahn, T.P., Ball, G.F., Photoperiodic regulation of the reproductive axis in male zebra finches, Taeniop